<Rating>2</Rating>< Review>
I do like to give local companies business and have used them in the past.
I would use this company for only small glass replacement
I requested a quote to reglaze on two large 8'x6' and 3 smaller windows with 1950s grid style glass and when the representative came to the home he quoted me 3 days 3 men, which I thought was way too much man power and labor he was clearly over bidding the job, they said they would call me with the quote.
I had to call them a week later and asked about the quote they said they would have someone call me that day so a couple of days later a office  manager called and quoted me $13,000.00 and I informed them I had 2 other quotes $9,000.00 less he wouldn't even think about it and seemed to busy.
It's to bad I wanted to use them as I'm a long time resident of SB it seems they are quoting high when they get a little busy
I won't be using them for large anything jobs and cannot recommend them</Review>

< text>
I don't normally write reviews but I was compelled to let people know about this establishment. I own a restaurant and was in need of expedited repair for a broken entrance door. I needed custom hardware that would have taken over a week to receive. Chris phoned the owner, explained my predicament, and headed out get materials to fabricate the needed hardware on site! < Text>
This place is ruthless, their sale rep is not well train.  There are a lot of undisclosed information that was not present to the buyer like myself.  It took me close to 2 hrs just to come to deal with them at .90% apr for 60 months even though their website and advertisement present a 0% apr at 60 month.  This is such a dishonest business mentality and speak a lot about Hyundai as an organization.  I feel like I was being cheated at the time of the sale, because there are a lot of add-ons was being added to my contract without full discloser and the benefit of those add-on.  On top of that their finance manager Jennifer is very pushy, I was not please with her customer service attitude.  I should have walk out of the sale, but I really needed a car that day.
I have drove the Hybrid Elantra limited edition for about 2 weeks now.  I am not please with the performance of the car.  If you are thinking about buying an Elantra or a Hyundai.  I suggest you think twice and do your research about the car especially the electrical aspect of the car.  I just purchase the car, but the car sometime turn off when I'm idling.  Sometime when I enter the car I have to push the start button several time for the car to start and other time it's a one time push.  This has always been a Hyundai issue since 2011, and they have not fix this issue for other model of their car neither.  These cars should be recall, it's dangerous and Hyundai should recognize this and listen to their customers.  EV is becoming mainstream, yet these issues has not been perfected.  Wether it's a manufacturing flaw or a software flaw they need to make this as a priority if they want to be competitive.< /Text>

He ensured that we did not over order or overspend, and took the time to understand exactly what we were looking for and make sure we got it. His friendliness absolutely blew me away. I would highly recommend visiting Mary's purely for the chance to chat with Kevin.< /text>

< Review>
Very beautiful and with a serene surrounding. The place is spread out with beautiful peacocks displaying their feathers in full glory.
The vegetarian restaurant inside the premise offers healthy and tasty food. Be prepared for a long wait on holidays and weekends.
Personally, I would have preferred if the monastery was quiet without playing the recorded teachings. They could have offered headphones to the interested and maintain the hall for meditation or deeper introspection.
Overall, a wonderful place to visit again & again.</Review>

<time>1443014360072<//time>< rate>

<Text>The house of ten thousand Buddhas an old abandoned hospital that was purchased in the seventies and has been incredibly transformed into a school to teach one lineage of Buddhism. The staff I met was cheerful helpful laughing and working hard to make the facility even nicer to accommodate the people that are here as they continue their practice on a day to day basis. The small museum in the administration building is interesting if you want to know any of the history of this lineage, otherwise it will be some artifacts and just old things. The grounds are spacious. The roads and walkways are wide with plenty of room to stroll.As you enter you are greeted by a huge Chinese gatethat you drive beneath on your way to the first facility. T
The Hall of ten thousand Buddhas is quite a vortex of energy. To sit and meditate
there, well it's quite powerful. There are gold Buddhas adorning wall row after row after row after row after row. Impressive as you sat and absorb this energy, people come in pay their respects, bow and pray move on about their day. It is a very impressive room and not to be missed. For me it was an overwhelming experience to consider all the good work that has gone on at this facility the energy was very powerful all I can say is triple wow! The good vibrations lasted long after my departure from this energy vortex.< /Text>< Pics>

<text>A beacon of light for living beings suffering in the temporary residence we call 'me'. The grounds are great, the restaurant REALLY good and all vegetarian, there are nice displays and a big gift store, as well as elementary, secondary, and university education facilities. And everybody is very calm and nice. But what really is impressive is the immense spiritual work done to build and sustain it and its sister monasteries worldwide welcoming for those who are looking for a different way of living life, a very lofty cosmology, and living examples of people who have transcended the usual worldly concerns. The sincerity of the underlying Dharma Realm Buddhist Association is a wonderful thing...rare in a world of "Me , first!"  So enjoy a short visit or begin a compelling spiritual journey at one of the many recitation or meditation sessions or volunteer programs where outsiders who are willing to observe some simple rules to respect the rule of monastic life the monks and nuns must follow.<//text></record></dataset><record>

<Text>The girls school is first rate. Students are separated by sex as education is not a social event. The level of personal involvement, from the clerics and Dharma masters to civilian and lay-people is top drawer. The campus (once a state mental hospital) could still be considered a type of hospital as healing is embraced here. I, personally, was stunned by the openess, warmth & love generated by these fellow humans from as far away as it is possible to be. Yet the experience left me understanding that the ONLY difference is that we are different from one another. Yet, any contact with the inhabitants immediately proves that, we are all the same. I cannot make any of these concerning the boys school. As a result, my daughter remained and my son was removed. My wife and I felt that peer and general humiliation directed towards male children was counterproductive, insulting and unnecessary.</Text></record>

108849143980617917893</UserId.>
< user_name>
Michael Ortali< /user_name>
< time>
1549516139566<//time>
<Rate>1< /Rate>< Review>
Moved in July 2017. Overall: extremely expensive rent, no security, high-crime area, poorly insulated apartments, cars/bikes often vandalized, stolen packages, careless tenants. Other reviews seem to agree on this too.

Let's start with the pros since it's a very small list: the building is new, so it is mostly clean. The floor plans are well arranged and depending on your budget, you can have enough space for two people; staff is friendly, but that stops here (if you have an issue, they raise their hand and show you the lease), and cool view of San Francisco from the rooftop.

The list of cons is by far longer:

Poor security for a high crime area: the entire premise has very limited security. Bikes are vandalized and stolen (saw a melted Kryptonite u-lock) despite them promoting a "very secure bike storage". Packages are consistently stolen, we've lost hundred of dollars of unreimbursed packages. I've seen cars being vandalized directly on the premise (including the garage). There are no functional cameras, so whatever happens, you can't even go to the cops (they ask for the recording so does the insurance LSeven forces you to sign up for).

Apartment is not well insulated from the hallway and the outside. If it's cold, the apartment gets immediately cold. And if you don't have sunlight (which is our case), it tends to be freezing. The heaters are dysfunctional, it takes them hours to warm up the room. Windows aren't soundproof, if someone decides to scream outside, you can hear them just fine.

Rent is abusive. The fee you see on paper is not what you end up paying: they force you to pay for a specific (bad) internet plan (you won't have a choice, it's required). Additional costs occurs for electricity and garbage. The free month they offer to everyone is gone in no time.

Community areas: from topless guys at the gym to obnoxious people throwing music parties at the rooftop, or screaming at their phone, trashy behavior in these common areas happens all the time. Mid-night, it's not rare to hear drunk people screaming in the hallway.

Amenities: the apartment comes with cheap amenities (fridge doesn't even have water dispenser, sounds small, but consider the rent you'll pay), the microwave doesn't unfreeze food, the oven is probably the only one piece that works ok.

Instead of investing on what actually matters, they organize "parties" and "events" to make the place more attractive. Understand: you pay for these events even if they show as "free" or "perk". If you care about "dating tips", or "cryptocurrency investment", you might find them awesome though. I don't. So I'd rather pay less and have this building be more secure for the tenants.<//Review>

< Review>
LSeven is gorgeous community in the heart of Soma!  Location is great!  Freeway access to the Peninsula and East Bay are just around the corner.  You can walk to local bars, restaurants, and grocery shopping (Trader Joes and Costco are a couple of blocks away).  I love the fact that it's in a quieter neighborhood, but still feels like you're in the city, and at the same time not far from the busier nightlife neighborhoods like the Mission.  I looked at few units before moving in and the ones I saw had ample sized bedrooms, great closet space (I have walk-in closets), a great open floorplan for entertaining, full sized appliances/washer and dryer (in-unit), interior design is sleek/clean and I also have floor to ceiling windows (my plants definitely enjoy their new home too!)  Overall, really happy with my decision.  There are a lot of choices out there, but would highly recommend coming to see the community in person!</Review>

Modern apartments, good appliances and an ok gym.
-1 for noise. These apartments have 0 noise insulation, so get ready to be woken up in the middle of the night by sirens and engine revving.
- 1 for heat insulation. You can keep the heater running on 80 and it will still feel cold because most of the heat escapes through the windows and the exit door.

<Text>Taking one star off for the location. It‚Äôs a convenient location but not a pleasant one. I love walking in the city and I always try to walk if my destination is within 30mins walk. Well, walking in west SOMA is rather a stressful experience. That is why I moved to another neighborhood 15 months after living at L7.

The apartment complex itself is nice with great design and high end finishes which is not that common for the price they were offering in 2017, but it was also brand new building back then and when we moved in we were the first people in the building and still had a construction work for about 3 months happening in our building, which is why we got quite a good rate for a complex this type.

<text>Easily one of the greatest tides in California Adventure along with Incredocoaster and Midway Mania. We went in 2019 and only had to wait for like 30 minutes without fastpass. The queue is very creatively themed and there are lot of fun exciting drops. The best part is the screen that opens up in the very top so you have a really good Ariel view of the entire park. Excellent ride, totally worth the wait, and this would be a priority along with the other two I mentioned if you want to visit the park.</text>< user>

<date>1557781602833< /date><Review>It's literally "free-fall elevator, the ride". I haven't rode it when it was still called "The Tower of Terror" but it's still a fun, exhilarating ride nevertheless. The brief moment of weightlessness is really fun and it is one of the "extreme" rides you'll ride in the park. The lines can get really long so prioritizing getting a fast pass here is recommended.</Review><GmapID>0x80dcd76fe8dfa0d5:0xb44b2bbd07b43658< /GmapID>< Name>

< Review>
An upgrade from Tower of Terror in every which way. The wait leading up to the ride is filled with many little Easter Eggs and charm that will very much keep you occupied until your chance to get strapped in. Evening is honestly the best time to hit this ride.

It was magical to get jostled up and down while "Free Ride" blares in your eardrums.</Review>

< rating>
5</rating>
<Review>This ride is awesome! Formerly, The Twilight Zones, Tower of Terror, this was revamped a couple years ago when Disney acquired Marvel and turned into this free falling Guardians of the Galaxy escape mission ride. There are multiple songs that can come on at random on the ride once you are in the Gantry lift and the ride starts. All of them are classic rock songs, and if you loves Star Lords mix tapes in the movies, you will live the songs they selected for this ride. I wont ruin which songs they are for you as it is always a treat when the ride starts. Anyways, have a blast. We always do!< /Review>< pictures>

<user>110964853590509853409< /user><username>Shawna Rasmussen<//username>< time>
1563558330996< /time>
<rating>5</rating><Review>This is the best ride in the whole park! Where can I begin...

First of all, GET A FAST PASS. The lines do get quite ridiculous! But even though the lines were normally around 2 hours long, every time I visit California Adventure, I ride this attraction about 15 times!

*If you read on, expect spoilers of the ride*

The ride consists of a ‚Äúgantry lift‚Äù or an elevator. You and about 20 other people will be strapped into this lift. Rocket from The Guardians of the Galaxy movie will take all of you in the ride up to the top of the tower, then to suddenly drop down to the bottom, creating a sort of anti-gravity feeling. BEWARE: Strap down or hold tight to any loose items, because you will very possible loose them. After going up and down a bit with the same anti-gravity
feeling, you will be shot up through the tower, stopping at the top, where a door opens up, a picture is taken of everyone in the lift and you get an amazing view of the full theme park.

Definitely recommend this ride to anyone who is over the age of 8. This ride is very, very exhilarating. Expect to be screaming in either joy or terror the whole ride. Most likely both at the same time.

Enjoy the ride!<//Review>< pics>
None< /pics>

<user_id>113498338186855483640< /user_id><rate>5</rate><Time>1603654074987<//Time><response>None< /response>< review>
The beer is some of the best in San Diego, which is a high compliment in this beer town. The pizza is also really good. There are a lot of pizzas, including several veggie options. You can also get it normal or thin crust style. The service is friendly. It's counter service, not table service, which feels especially good in these covid times. They are also doing a good job with safety protocols, keeping people distant, limiting the number of people, etc. That means you might have a wait during busy times, but well worth the wait!</review>

< Text>
I was finally around the area and had a chance to try pizza port in Ocean Beach. We called ahead to avoid the crowd and the wait for the food. Got the all meet and the Roma, both were delicious. The service was good although they get real busy so expect to wait and may be ignored. They currently have all dining in the patio and in their parking lot.  So parking in the area is a little tough and you're probably going to need to look for street parking. Overall the food was very good.<//Text>

< user>
112402214680656830849<//user>
<username>Nick Pierce</username>< Date>
1582515292377<//Date>
< rate>
5</rate>
< review>
Delicious pizza and suds! We beat the Sunday crowd by getting there at 5pm. It was busy by 6pm, but the food came out quick enough for us, but appetizers helped. There's a food only line on the right. Food and brew line to the left. Ask for samples of their brews.
Pizza was nice and doughy, but not thick like pan pizza, not too thin either. Loads of toppings!!!
The Carlsbad was outstanding... hope you like artichoke, pesto and fetaüòâ. BBQ cheeseburger had meatballs, not ground beef, I liked it more than I thought I would. I was expecting weird, but the meatballs made it seem more traditional.
Wings were baked, not bready. (The way i like it)
We got the veggie basket as a side, it was ideal for a family of 4 or two really hungry people.
For you beer bodies, they offer cans, growlers, and 6 packs to go.
There's a small parking lot adjacent and there's a pay to park across the street. If you want free parking, plan on street parking and walking a block or two.< /review>

<user_id>113259853121332864859<//user_id>< review>
Killer pizza! This place does not disappoint. Dropped in with a group of college friends who were staying in Ocean Beach.

Pizza Port has a very chilled, laid-back vibe. We were quickly able to find a long table that accommodated our group. Note, that the tables are shared, so don't be afraid to chat up your neighbor.

Pizza took about 35 mins to bake, and we enjoyed few rounds of beer while waiting, along with the jalapeno poppers (highly recommend!). We tried the Garlic Veggie Pizza w/ traditional crust. Super fresh veggies and gooey cheese.

We will defiantly be back on our next trip to SD!</review>

< Review>
Yummy. The food never disapoints. We got two small pizzas,  wings and a veggie basket along with Swamis beer.  Everything was cooked exactly how we had hoped. We love taking pizza port to the cliffs to enjoy a mini picnic. The carlsbad is my favorite pizza.  Very different with the pesto, sun dried tomato, chicken, artichokes and feta cheese. 1592164197213<//Time>
<user_name>Neil Slate</user_name><resp>None</resp>< review>
I have been a fan of Pizza Port for many years. They keep the menu simple with pizza, salad, breadsticks, mozzarella sticks, and buffalo chicken wings and craft beer and soda and iced tea. I love all their food and they have lunch specials, like two slices and a drink or a slice, salad, and a beverage (non-alcoholic), and a couple other options. You can substitute a beer for an additional charge. They have the proper social distancing protocols on keeping your mask on when you are not seated at your table. You have to ask for napkins, utensils, parmesan cheese, or red pepper flakes.
The service is friendly and helpful. I fully recommend this Pizza Port in Ocean Beach, San Diego.
The toughest part about the Ocean Beach (OB) location is parking is scarce. Especially with the social distancing protocols in place, they took over the small 7 parking spot lot for outdoor dining.</review>

<Review>The beer buddies were super good with our beers. The price in the area can't be beat. If you get the $3 pints and a small pizza and some beer buddies it's a perfect meal for two. This is a favorite for us for date night! Love their chronic ale, easily my favorite.
----------------Editted a few months later-----------------

Edit: From five to three stars for super rude staff. First I tried to order slices and the bartender told me they weren't doing slices so I ordered two small pizzas. Before my order came up I watched several people order and pick up individual slices. So I then had two small pizzas and needed some to-go boxes. They normally have them sitting out to help yourself. They didn't have any available so I requested two boxes from the staff. The busser said to me "two boxes? Why do you need two boxes?" I explained I had two pizzas but he retorted with "uh huh." I allowed my -well over 21- boyfriend to sample my beer (he didn't want one but wanted to try it) and we had the busser inform us that he couldn't taste my drink without getting ID'ed by the bartender and then said if he saw it again he would "have to bounce us". Asking for an ID would have sufficed. He absolutely did not need to treat us like we were breaking the law. This is a brewery, you have to assume people will sample each other's drinks. It's not accepted to threaten to remove someone from the property over it without requesting an ID first.

I don't know if they were recently hit with a fine or what but this behavior is a little wild. This place has been a favorite of ours for years and the entire atmosphere totally flipped. I hope that this trend doesn't continue because it makes it extremely uncomfortable to dine and relax.</Review><Pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNgqr1ia3e42xe7M-kDoUDFu_sVOVGjHsS6rf0i=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /Pics>< resp>

<UserId.>114054506485824647528</UserId.>< Name>
Garrett Bredell< /Name>
<Date>1528700948747<//Date><rating>5</rating>< text>
Pizza Port's OB location is a staple for every one of my visits to the area. It captures the spirit of the area so well - surf, beer, and a loose and casual feel. Just a little off the main drag, it's within easy reach for tired surfers and rubbernecks alike, and makes a fine choice when Hodad's is running a line around the corner.

First, I've really only had the pizza. And it's good, competing with NY Slice style pizza around San Diego (East Coasters might turn their nose up at the place, FWIW.) I've also sampled the kale salad which was inappropriately healthy given the settings. The real treat here is the beer, which is always diverse, experimental, affordable, and delicious. Pizza Port's social media game has been overshadowed by newer players, but the brewing and taste is still on point, and matches supremely with the pizza available.

Head in during the lunch special and get away with two slices and a beer for less than $10, then get back to the beach with your newly acquired gut. Or return to the main street and go shopping, if you can resist the temptation to nap.< /text>

<user_id>107422422651875999620</user_id>< review>
WARNING: Do NOT place orders via ChowNow.

I've been a regular at the OB and Solana Beach Pizza Port locations since childhood.

Yesterday, I placed an order online for pickup at the OB Pizza Port via ChowNow.  I arrived 15 minutes after receiving the notification that the food was ready.  Due to an error between the shop and ChowNow, my order was never received so I waited for it to be prepared (outside, standing on the curb due to COVID restrictions) after being quoted 15 minutes.  30 minutes later, I checked on the progress and was informed that I had been made the incorrect pizza and that they would finish the one I ordered in 10 minutes.  One hour after I initially arrived to pick up my food, I finally received what I ordered.

The women who served me were very kind and offered the incorrectly-made pizza for free in addition to what I ordered, which I really appreciated.  Unfortunately, because I had to wait an hour to receive my order, my girlfriend missed a seminar she needed to attend.  Going forward, I unfortunately won't be providing my business to the OB location.< /review>

Excellent place. Amazing beer and amazing pizza. My only complaint (and this only stems from them being so good) is that it's so crowded. The place is pretty much covered in long picnic tables that are usually full to the brim and the line to get beer is usually super long. But as long as you plan for that, it's a great time. < review>
Visiting and needed a place to grab food and relax a little after visiting the zoo. Pizza Port fit the bill and was friendly and welcoming. My girlfriend was indecisive on which beer she wanted and they were generous enough to give us both plenty of tastings. Their beers were good and the variety of guest beers was excellent. The pizza was well done, not overly greasy like some can be and had a tasty crust.  We also ordered a salad which was decent. Better than many other pizza joints but not gourmet level.</review>

< Review>
It was okay. I was disappointed because I took my kids here SPECIFICALLY to have some of their house-made root beer and when I ordered it, was told that the machine was broken. Oddly enough, that was the same story I got when I visited the Solana Beach location a couple of years ago. Regardless, if they're not going to offer an item, I think that the menu board should note that it's not available. Also, I ordered the lunch special and when I told the clerk what type of pizza I wanted, she replied that the only options were cheese, pepperoni, or the pizza of the day. The menu board says "any slice pizza" - again, if it's only certain types of pizza that are available with the special, then the menu should note that, not say "Any." I ordered the pizza of the day and it was yummy. It was hot and fresh, and the servings were large. The orders came out in a reasonable amount of time. If you're not a regular, it's a little unclear what you're supposed to do after you're finished eating - bus your own table? Leave it there? Some signage would help with that too. All in all, it was an ok experience. I wouldn't drive out of my way to go there again (like I did this time) and circle the block again & again looking for parking, but if I was already in the area, I'd eat there.<//Review>

Went here for the first time for dinner with a group of co-workers. Ordered the Pizza Lahaina, Pizza Laguna, and Pizza San Clemente (love the pizzas named after California beaches). Each pizza was more scrumptious than the next! I never would have believed that a pizza with black bean sauce as its base could be so good but it was a revelation. Anna Coleman<//name>
<Time>1565020509313< /Time><rating>5<//rating>< review>
We loved this place! Our lyft driver was telling us how great it was before we even walked in the door, so they obviously have a following. They have tons of pizza options in addition to simple build-your-own and their traditional crust option really filling, almost like a colorado mountain pie style pizza. They also have a huge beer selection. The vibe is very casual and fun; we came in at like 9:30pm during a baseball game and on one side of us we had a big family with young kids watching the TVs and on the other side a big group of rowdy young guys who were playing a drinking game. Definitely a place for everyone!</review>

<rate>4< /rate>< Review>
Great for a crowd. Went for a birthday party with a group of six. We ordered individually and ordered too much food. Medium pies are quite large. They offer many different preset pizza options along with a create your own. We had the Mac and Cheese bites to start and they were good. Lots of video games and entertainment for the kids. Also a craft brewery on the premise. Very laid back experience. Order at the window and they call out your name to pick up the order. The announcer took some liberties with his announcements and created some smiles. Would go back with a crowd. Would not go by myself.< /Review>

I love their "wings" night on thursday's!  At 49 cents each it's a good deal, but it's only for "Dine In"  I would go early because it gets very busy and very crowded.  They are a very popular spot!  They're wings are great (though I've only tried a few different ones.)  I love their pizzas and the selection.  They can come up with some unusual combinations, but they're fun to try!  I hear (through people I go with and family members) that their beers are fantastic!  Great selection and reasonably priced.  I would recommend Pizza Port, but if you don't like crowds go on a week night (Monday or Tuesday) or during the week before 6pm.</Review>

< Rating>
4</Rating>
< review>
Very tasty pizzas (the garlic veggie and bbq chicken are some of our favorites). The kale salad is surprisingly delicious. The mac n cheese bites were a bit of a let down, but the wings were good. They have a variety of beers on draft and occasionally a cider as well. It's a bit loud inside and the seating outside doesn't offer much of a view, but it's still a fun spot to check out and is very close to Ocean Beach. Parking nearby is a bit of a nightmare, but if your willing to pay or walk a few blocks you can easily find some.</review>

Good Pizza, beer, people, and a pinball machine.  What more can you ask for?  The pizza is a little thick and saucy for my taste (I am more of NY pizza girl)  but the ingredients are always very fresh and yummy.  On weekend evenings are very crowded, but lunchtime is not that bad.  They have a good lunch special, a slice, and salad; both are HUGE. Big enough for sharing if you are not so hungry.  If you are in the area give it a try.  Very fun atmosphere!<//Text>

<gmapID>0x80deaa3a261cd2e3:0x3e89464c53bf352</gmapID>< resp>

< Text>
Once again, while looking for pizza we found this place and just the pictures of the food alone brought us into Pizza Port on a Saturday afternoon.  We came with our 3 children, and while I wouldn't necessarily call it a "family restaurant" I was comfortable with my two youngest being there because it's a loud, upbeat place where their noise levels would bother no one.
It took a few minutes to decide what we wanted, but we had an order of buffalo wings, which were dry rub and not super saucy, so they were good.  My littlest two each had slices of their favorite pizzas and the hubby and I each got a small, he had the San Clemente, and I the margherita pizza.  The individual slices were insane, they were bigger than the plates they were on.  The San Clemente has a black bean sauce, and it had this unique flavor that made me think I was eating somewhere between a taco and a pizza...it was quite good.  Then of course there was the Margherita pizza.  Not the best one I have ever had, but it was good and I would eat it again.   Truth be told though, I tasted the San Clemente first and it was so flavorful and yummy that maybe my tastebuds were a little screwy and the Margherita was just plain at that point.
We also enjoyed a Beer Float, something we'd discussed trying many many times, but had never actually come across.  We did at Pizza Port, and the options for beers in my float were amazing.  I went with a coffee porter and was pleasantly surprised.  Not gonna lie, I was skeptical, but I came out of this experience a fan.
This location is good for an afternoon slice and a cold beer or two.  Bringing the kids is totally fine, and going without them is totally fine too.
The atmosphere is laid back, the food is good, and the beer is cold.  What more could you ask for?<//Text>

< Text>
Pizza Port is always poppin'. I drove by it 100s of times while living in Cardiff by the Sea. It's packed at lunch and dinner. They make their own beer there too. Try the honey beer. It's full of awesomeness.

It's kid friendly and has video game arcades too. The only thing I didn't like too much about it is the lack of seating available, but I guess that's what happens when you get great pizza and beer.

You basically order your pizza at the register and find a seat as fast as someone stands up. They will call your name over the loud speaker. No waiters here. Lots of fun. There is also another location (i think in Ocean Beach).<//Text>

<username>Kristel Boe< /username>< time>
1411684619664</time>
<rating>4</rating>< review>
It's hard to write anything bad about this place since it already has a winning combination of pizza and beer. Add a killer location (Ocean Beach) to the list, and you've got the recipe for a great afternoon or evening out.

If I were to say anything negative about the joint, is it's a bit crowded. Don't expect to come to Pizza Port and get a private table for two. All seating is community style, and the place is loud... so be in the mood to be social! And if you aren't, just have a pitcher of beer and you'll be adding to the noise level in no time :-)</review>

<Review>Really nice vibe here at PIzza Port. People are rough around the edges but overall pretty friendly. More often that not, every time I'm there, somehow another person's pizza slice ends up on my plate. It's strange but I don't fight it. < review>
Didn't get a chance to try the beer but I am sure it is good based on reviews. I walked in and found a long line for a Beer and Food order counter. So I made my way to the bar where I asked the bartender if I could order just beer, and he said "sure" and took my beer order of two beers for me and my brother. He went to go grab the beers and was stopped by another employee. He then came back and informed us we had to wait in the long line to order anything. I have never seen such a complicated ordering setup just to get a beer at any other brewery.</review>

<rate>5< /rate><text>I give Pizza Port 5 stars for the beer and 4 stars for the food. However I have a lot of non-craft beer drinking friends that come here just for the food, so my standards might be high. To me the pizza is the perfect complement to their beer - doughy, cheesy and loaded with toppings. Their beers are very underrated compared to other breweries in San Diego, mostly because they make so many that aren't all world-class. But all of them are above average, priced fairly, and served fresh from the brewery in a casual family-friendly environment. Frequently Pizza Port creates some beers that really knock it out of the park (Santa's Little Helper, Mongo IPA, Bacon & Eggs Breakfast Coffee Porter, etc.) They have a generous amount of taps devoted to "guest brewery beers" including Russian River, Ballast Point, etc. Their homemade root beer is awesome, I recommend trying a float. Or try some of their "beer buddies" which is cooked pizza dough bites brushed with garlic butter.</text>< Date>
1412382964574< /Date>

<UserId.>113897371292918169007< /UserId.>< Gmap_id>

< rating>
4<//rating>
< Response>
None</Response>
< user_name>
Ian - Fr0wnZ< /user_name>
<pictures>None< /pictures>< review>
Came in with a group of friends for our last meal during our San Diego trip. Most of the group heard great things about Pizza Port, so it had to be a clear winner? Parking can be an issue with limited spots available, but luckily we found street parking about a block away.

The atmosphere of the restaurant looked fun and inviting. There were many flat screen TV's around the restaurant playing the football game. The seating reminded me of long park bench tables, big enough to fit large parties of 20 or 30. The craft beer bar is located on the left side of the restaurant while food is in the middle.

As far as food, Pizza Port offers premium gourmet pizzas. I originally wanted the Pizza SF but two friends had already ordered that, so I just randomly chose the featured month pizza, Teriyaki Chicken. It was just okay and I probably wouldn't get it again. The flavors didn't mesh well for me; carrots & broccoli inside a cheesy pizza. The pizza's are portioned generously, so if you're one person just go with the individual. There's also arcade games towards the back of the pizza restaurant. Pizza Port reminds me of an adult Shakey's. I will definitely come back but order the pizza I want regardless of who in the group gets it.</review>

<Review>Don‚Äôt be fooled by the name, Pizza Port is a great pizza place as well, but even if they didn‚Äôt have pizza at all, they would be a pretty great bar and brewery. The outside patio section under some palm trees is awesome on nice days. The inside is huge with lots of long tables and great for big gatherings or small get togethers alike. The beer menu is huge as the Pizza Port brewing empire has several facilities. There are probably close to 3 dozen beers on tap across the range from blonde ales to porters. There are of course multiple hop forward IPAs that go great on a hot day. Even the malty wheat and ales are pretty delicious. The inside is a good place to catch sports as well with many TVs. < user_id>
103485627635972293253< /user_id>
<username>Michael Armentano<//username>< Date>
1459014763200< /Date>
< rate>
4< /rate>
< Review>
This is the quintessential surfer/craft beer hangout.  I think I literally saw Jeff Spicoli (if you're not old enough to know who that is, forget it).

On a serious note, the only thing that is not awesome about this place is the parking situation, but then again what can you expect in OB and thank the flying spaghetti monster that there are no soul sucking multi-story parking garages ruining the vibe that is OB.

I haven't been to the other Pizza Ports yet, but this one was fantastic albeit packed to the gills.  As you probably already know there is a plethora of home brewed craft beers, as well as plenty of guest taps.  Heavy on the D/I/PAs, in fact when I was there I think they had 7 IPAs and  3 or 4 DIPAs.  The beer line and the pizza line are separate and there are virtually no vegetarian pizza options, unless you roll your own (which you can if you want).

If I lived in OB (I'm not sure how this is possible anymore with real estate prices the way they are) I'd be there several times a week.< /Review>

< Name>
Lyndsi Winer<//Name>
< Review>
I can't particularly say I LOVE their pizza but it's ok.  Their atmosphere is great and their beer even better. They brew their own beer and dozens of types!  All SUPER SUPER awesome!  It's a place for craft beer aficionados!  Their staff is always happy to be there and happy to serve you and I very rarely can complain about them.  The pizza is ok, they have great specialty ingredients and the larger the pizza the better the crust I think.  Don't get a small if you don't like a lot of dough more like a hand tossed pan pizza.  The large is good and the lunch slices even better!  In fact they have the best lunch deal in town!  An amazing garden salad that me and my bf share and HUGE slices of pizza and soda for 5$ and if you want a beer its a 1$ more for regular beer and 2$ for stronger beers.  They always have a unique slice of the day accompanied with the choice also of pepperoni or cheese everyday and the slice with the salad is perfect!  I ate this almost daily when I worked across the street!  They are fast and the lunch is good and soooooo cheap!! They also have great salads!  The port salad is one of my favs!  It's all veggies and has so much in it that is unique you'll never miss the meat!  Roasted red peppers, blue cheese, spring mix, marinated portobellos and more!  It's to die for!!!< /Review>

Pizza and beer, how can you go wrong?!  They do an awesome job here, it's always busy and the food is epic.<//text>
< UserId.>
112945459156387556951<//UserId.>
<pictures>None</pictures><time>1483925408325</time>< user_name>
Tristan Petricca<//user_name>
< gmapID>
0x80deaa3a261cd2e3:0x3e89464c53bf352< /gmapID>
</record>
</dataset><record>
< Pictures>
None< /Pictures>
< Text>
We came here to hang out with friends, and this was a perfect spot. Great food, great beer selections, and great company!

We came here on a Sunday night, a night before Memorial day. It's been awhile, and I completely forgot how crazy busy it is in these Ocean Beach streets. We got luckily how easily we found a table fit for 8 people.  The place is always packed and  loud, however people are quite polite and respectful.

We tried out the honey beers, Carlsbad pizza, cajun bites, garlic bites and chicken wings.  The honey beers were a treat for me. I'm not much of a beer drinker, but the Honey beer is something I would keep ordering. It's light, tart, and a hint of honey for the after taste.  The carlsbad pizza intrigued me --with the mix of artichoke hearts, feta cheese, alfredo sauce and peppers. The pizza was a tasty creation. The saltiness and sweetness flavors worked well with the ingredients. Though, the chicken wings didn't impress me much. It was average. The cajun & garlic bites were ok. They were made in a pizza bread, and then cut into pieces, cajun ---with jalapenos & garlic -- stating the obvious, and put into a basket to share.

Whenever I'm in Ocean Beach, I'd be back here for the assortment of beers and pizza selections!</Text>
